{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_inxs_ver01/data/sn82014519/00414183566/1930100101/0545.xml":{"full_text":"NEW BRITAIN DAILY HERALD, WEDNESDAY, OCTOBER i, 1930.\nHARD TIMES HELP\nCOLLEGECLASSES\nScarcity ol Work Sends More\nStudents to Institutions\nNew York, Oct. 1 (UP) Drought\nand the business depression, instead\nor decreasing the enrollment in\nAmerican colleges this year, are\nlikely to cause the heaviest attend\nance in years, a survey by the\nUnited Press indicated today.\nOnly four schools in the compre\nhensive list included in the survey\nreported a decreased enrollment o\nany considerable size and only three\nof them attributed it- to business\ndepression. The University of Mis\nsissippi reports 50 fewer students\nthan last year. \"Financial depres\nsion,\" was the terse explanation of-\nfered by R. L. Sullivan, registrar.\n'Mississippi A. M. also reported a\ndecrease and blamed it on \"bad\ncrops.\"\nIndiana University reported 187\nfewer students than at this time last\nyear and officials there ascribed the\ndecrease to \"hard times.\" The\nUniversity of Illinois save its new\nstudent enrollment as 645 less than\nin 1929 But-offered no explanation.\nOn the other hand there were\nseveral educators who expressed the\nbelief that shortage of jobs had sent\nmany students back to school who\notherwise would not have completed\n.their education.\n\"Paradoxical as It may seem,\"\nsaid President Thomas AV. Atkinson\not Louisiana State University, \"the\nbusiness depression is a possible ex\nplanation for the increased enroll\nment. In the scarcity of positions\n.which has prevailed recently, par-\nents have seen that it is the college\nman or woman who has landed the\n;jeb.\"\nPeriods Cancel\n\"Studies of enrollments show that\nperiods of prosperity and depression\njut about cancel each other,\" said\nGlenn Frank, president of the Uni\nversity of Wisconsin. If these per\niods have any effect on college en\nrollments, the tendency seems to be\ni for prosperity to slow up and for\n\"depressions to speed up registra\n\"tions.\" At Drake University officials ex\npressed the opinion that a business\n'depression invariably drove people\n\"to school so they could fit them\nselves better for their work and\n'avoid the danger of losing their jobs\n\"in future depressions.\n\"Unemployment and business de\nrepression, are in a way responsible\n\"for the slight increase in enrollment\n'here,\" said the Rev. Thomas Plass-\nrran, president of St. Bonaventure's,\nSt Bonaventure's, N. Y. \"Many for\n\"mer students who started an educa\ntion and did not finish it have been\nlaid off from their jobs. They have\n'returned to school, having learned\nJ the most highly trained man has.\n.the greatest advantage.\"\nAmong the schools reporting in-\ncreased enrollments with the\nlmount of their increase were:\n.Hobart College, Geneva, N. Yabout.\npO; Virginia Polytechnic Institute,\nf48; University of Virginia, 100;\n.Washington Lee, 13: George\nWashington University, 400; Beloit\n'College, 105; Alabama Polytechnic,\nJTOO; University of Wisconsin, \"little\nchange or perhaps slight gain\";\n\"University of Nebraska, 164; Knox\nCollege, Galesburg, 111., total of 656\n.students (largest in history); East\nern Illinois State Teachers' College,,\n'75; Temple University, 13,053 for\n.total enrollment (largest in history\nor school); Clemson College, 82;\nMiami University, Oxford, Ohio,\n225; University of Denver, 167;\n1 .University of Southern California,\n307; University of California, (Los\nJ Angeles branch), 114; Purdue Uni\nversity, 343.\neQUEEN HELEN MAY\nGIVEJPJCHAEL\nRumanian Monarch Reported as\nWilling to Leave Son\nVienna, Oct. 1 iP) Sorrowful but\ndetermined not to grovel at the feet\n'of the handsome King Carol, Queen\n.Helen of Rumania was represented\nhere today as intending to leave\n'Rumania forever and to seek a place\n',of exile elsewhere' in Europe.\nA Rumanian politician arriving in\nVienna from Bucharest said that\nafter many tears Helen had decided\n.to comply with Carol's wishes and\nleave little Michael, their bright\nfaced son, entirely to the care of his\nfather.\nAmong the queen's immediate\nentourage it was expected that she\n'would soon go to Germany where\nah could take up permanent resi\ndence near other members of the\nformer Greek royal family, them\nselves denied a' home in their na\ntive land, now a republic.\nWants Helen to Leave\nThe Rumanian politician said that\nCarol recently had remarked in the\npresence of many persons that the\n'best Helen could do would be to\n.leave Rumania of her own accord.\nThe remark was repeated to the\nqueen who, after a painful struggle\n.with herself, made up her mind\nthat she must abandon her dream\n\"of raising her much-loved son and\nleave the country.\nThe Rumanian people have come\nto consider Queen Helen very affec\ntionately, and have been touchet\nwith her self-sacrificing and digni\nfied bearing, the politician said. He\nadded that King Carol had been\nvisibly exasperated at the thought\nhe must forego an early roronation.\nTt is Carol now. rather than\nHelen, who is Insistent that the di-\nvorce Helen secured during his ab-\nsence in Paris remain valid, al\nthough Helen has never been less\ndetermined than at first to accept\n,no compromising status from him.\nAll hope of reconciliation is said to\nhave passed.\nThe longest session of the English\n'parliament was in 1 S SI. when the\n'house of commons sat for 41\nhoura\nREY. MICHAEL O'CONNOR\nOF DANBURY PASSES ON\nPriest Had Formerly Served as\nCurate at St. Mary's Church,\nXew Britain.\nDanbury, Oct. 1 Rev. Michael\nJ. O'Connor, 65, permanent rector\nof St. Peter's Catholic church here\ndied in the rectory Tuesday evening\nafter an illness of four months. He\nhad held the pastorate at St. Peter's\nchurch for six years and before that\nwas pastor of St. James church,\nStratford, for 17 years.\nHis first pastorate was at Pom\nfret and he had served as curate\nat St. Mary's in New Britain, St.\nPatrick's in New Haven and St.\nAugustine's in Bridgeport.\nRt. Rev. John J. Nilan, bishop of\nHartford, will celebrate the pontifi\ncal requiem mass Friday morning at\n10 o'clock.\nHOLMES ADVOCATES\nSCHOOtONOAK ST.\nWould Erect Building at Once to\nRelieve Crowding\nImmediate construction of a\nschool buiiding on Oak street prop\nerty owned by the city, a project\nthat would give employment to\nmany and would act as a relief to\nthe Stanley and other schools in\nthat locality, was proposed by\nSchool Supt. S. H. Holmes at a\nmeeting of the Stanley School Par\nents and Teachers' association last\nnight.\nSupt. Holmes said a building\ncould be constructed at the lowest\npossible cost at this time because\nof the prevailing business depres\nsion and since the building will have\nto be constructed sooner or later\nlittle or nothing can be gained by\ndelay. The building would be built\nthrough a bond issue, Mr. Holmes\nsaid.\nThe superintendent's proposal\nwas the result of a request of one\nof the parents that an addition to\nthe Stanley school be constructed to\ntake care of increased enrollment\nand to eliminate the portable build\ning that is now on the property.\nSupt. Holmes expressed ti; opin\nion that the construction of the\nschool buildfngton Oak street would\nrelieve three school buildings of\nwhich the Stanley school was ona,\nbut the building of an addition\nwould relieve only the Stanley\nschool. He said he did not like port\nable schools but that the school au\nthorities have done everything pos\nsible to make them comfortable\nwhen they are being used.\nSupt. Holmes said a similar con\ndition exists at the Northend school\nonly that building is about 50 years\nold and has not modern conveniences\nthat the Stanley school children en\njoy. Only these districts use portable'\nbuildings to take care of the over\nflow in school population, Mr.\nHolmes said.\nDuring the earlier part of his talk,\nMr. Holmes told of the fundamen\ntals of. a modern education.\nCITY ATLAMBESE\nExcavations in Algeria Show\nRuins Rivalling Timgad\nAlgiers, Algeria, Oct. 1 An\nother Roman city rivalling in im\nportance and In beauty, Timgad, the\nAfrican Pompeii discovered in 1875,\nis being uncovered in the depart\nment of Constantine at Lambese, a\nshort distance from Batna.\nThe ruins cover 133 acres and\nhave a forum which spreads out\nover 21,500 square feet. The Timgad\nnuns cover 99 acres. The Lambese\ncity, founded by veterans of Augus\ntus' Third legion who were station\ned in the region, contains two tri\numphal arches well preserved and\ntwo large necropolises with orna\nmental monuments for the dead.\nThe forum has been completely\nuncovered. There are but a dozen\nstones missing in the pavement.\nNumerous mosaics have been dug up\nas well as inscriptions with dedica\ntions to various gods, emperors and\nbenefactors of the city.\nLambese was situated in the cen\nter of a fertile region when Augus\ntus quartered his soldiers there,\nbut since then the territory became\nmarshy and natives avoided it. New\nlife has come over the old place\nnow that scientists are using their\nshovels there. Lambese is not dis\ntant from Timgad.\nRECKLESS DRIVER TARGET\nOF SAFETY FIRST ATTACK\nDriven Wreck Also Gets Attention ol\nSpeakers at National Congrc-s\nMeeting.\nPittsburgh, Oct. 1 VP) The reck\nless driver and the \"driven wreck\"\nwere the main targets of the Na\ntional Safety congress and exposi\ntion yesterday as safety experts\nsought ways and means of making\ntraffic on the nation's highways less\ndangerous. y\nUniform laws governing the peri\nodic inspection of automobiles in all\nstates were urged as the only prac\ntical means of eliminating the auto\nmobiles that endanger lives because\nthey are In such a worn condition\nthat they cannot be controlled pro\nperly. More strict enforcement of traffic\nrules and laws with greater uniform\nity in states and cities was advo\ncated as the best method of elim\ninating the reckless driver.\nEleven sections of the congress\nwere in session, discussing safety in\neverything from the handling of\ntiny chisels used in carving furniture\nto the moving of tons of steel with\ngiant cranes.\nURGES ELIMINATION\nOF MliLEDEALER\nBoston Business Man Outlines\nWay lor German Recovery\nBerlin, Oct. 1 CP) The doubling\nof the purchasing power of the Ger\nman masses by drastic elimination\nof the middle man and other ele\nments of costly distribution was\nsuggested as a cure for Germany'j\nbusiness depression by Edward A.\nFilene, Boston capitalist, im an ad\ndress yesterday before the American\nChamber of Commerce.\nObserving that \"no remedy is\nreal remedy which does not put the\nmasses, back to work,\" he predicted\nthat increased purchasing stimulat\ned by such a plan as suggested soon\nwould force increased production\nand employment thus would in\ncrease also.\nMr. Filene pointed out that con\nsumers the world over pay as high\nas six to eight times the cost of\nproduction for the necessities of Hie.\nHo said that this already had been\npartly recognized in Germany by the\nformation of \"konsum vereine\" and\ncoperative buying by a relatively\nsmall number of retailers.\nThe Boston merchant's idea was\nthat the government, in view of the\ncritical situation, should force all\ndistributors into similar organiza\ntions. As lie viewed it, mass buy\ning and mass production, being less\ncostly than unorganized buying and\nselling, would be certain to in\ncrease purchasing power and thus\nin effect would raise wages.\nSPEAKING TOUR\nThrows Out First Ball, Leaves\nlor Long Trip\nuro.hinirtnn. Oct. 1 (ff) President\nHoover turned today to his long\ncontemplated speaking trip wnicn, in\nthe next six days, will take him more\nthan 3,000 miles, into thre states of\nthe mid-west, east and south, for\nfour addresses on current national\nquestions.\nReversing the old adage, \"business\nbefore pleasure,\" the president ar\nranged first to throw out the first\nt,nii nA wttnpH the opening world's\nseries baseball game at Philadelphia,\nafter which his -speaking engage\nments will come in quick order, the\na- Kafna th American Bankers'\nassociation convention in Cleveland\ntomorrow night.\nSpecial Train cnarterea\nlied for departure\nof the presidential party by special\ntrain in the forenoon. The tour, the\nmost extensive for the president this\nyear, will be made in two jumps.\nReturning to Washington l'rioay\nmorning from Cleveland, Mr. Hoover\nwin r-ef under wav again Sunday\nnight for Boston where on Monday\nhe will make two day-time speeches.\nIn the morning before the national\nennvention of the American Legion\nand in the afternoon before the\nAmerican Federation of Labor.\nTmmeriiate.lv after the second Bos\nton speech, he will make a 21-hour\nswing back to Kings Mountain\nbattlefield in South Carolina, just,\nover the North Carolina border,\nwhere on Tuesday afternoon he will\nwind up his tour with an address at\na celebration of the sesquicentenrflal\nof the battle of King's Mountain in\nthe Revolutionary war.\nSpeches Eagerly Awaited\nrominc as thev do only a month\nbefore the congressional elections.\nthe presidential pronouncements will\nbe scanned eagerly by candidates\nand their supporters throughout the\ncountry. White House officials,\nhowever, insist the speeches will be\nnon-political. The King's Mountain\naddress, they point out, was ar\nranged nearly a year ago.\nIn three of the speeches the pres\nident will be heard over nationwide\nradio chains. Since the one before\nthe Federation of Labor will be de\nlivered during broadcast of the\nworld series ball erame. it has been\narranged for William Green, presi\ndent of the federation, to read It\nto the radio audience later.\nA large group of guests was In\nthe presidential party for the trip\nto Philadelphia, including Secretar\nies Hurley, Hyde, and Wilbur, Post\nmaster General Brown, Walter K.\nHope, assistant secretary of the\ntreasury; David S. Ingalls, assistant\nsecretary of the navy for aeronaut\nics; Henry M. Robinson, Los Ange\nles, member of the national drought\nrelief committee; George Akerson\nand Lawrence Rickey, two of Mr.\nHoover's secretaries: James Francis\nBurke, counsel of the republican na\ntional committee; Dr. Joel T. Boone,\nthe president's physician, and two\naides. Colonel Campbell B. Hodges\nand Captain C. Russell Train. Other\nofficials nnrl friends rtlanned tn inin\nthe president in Philadelphia for the\ngame, at which Mr. Hoover will be\nthe guest of Mayor Harry A. Mackey.\nMrs. Hoover .Not Attending\nMrs. Hoover will not be at the\ngame, but will join the president in\nOhio, traveling from Indianapolis,\nwhere she is attending the national\ncouncil of Girl Scouts. Accompanied\nby Mrs. Joseph It. Nutt, of Cleve\nland, wife of the treasurer of the\nrepublican national committee, Mrs.\nHoover will board the special train\nat Bedford, Ohio, tomorrow morn\ning. Slaughter Wild Deer\nSo Hungry Can Be Fed\nSt. Croix, Virgin Islands, Oct. 1\nP) So acute is the financial pres\nsure among the poor of this island,\nthat a slaughter of wild deer has\ncommenced. Venison is offered for\nsale in several local markets despite\ngame laws and sentiment against\npot hunting.\nThe deer are of the \"crown\" and\nthe \"red\" variety and are descended\nfrom deer introduced by the Danes\nin order that the wealthy sugar\nplanters might enjoy hunting as a\nsport. Flash lights are used and\nthe pot hunters bring down five or\nsix animals with a few shots. ,The\ndeer of St. Croix are small, rarely\nweighing over 100 pounds,\nL -ffily GREAT ANDROMEDA NEBULA fca\nnT\n\nS GREAT\nr NEBULA\ni- 1 SQUARE V,\n'CASSIOPEIA J OF\nf EC ASUS' Y\nX\n\nPERSEUS\nEl\nAST.\n03 I\nAndromeda's great nebula (lower) is chief nl celestial objects in\nOctober skies. To find it first look for the square of Pegasus (map),\nthen above the handle.\nBY ROBERT H. BAKER\n(Professor of Astronomy, University\nof Illinois)\nUrbana, 111. OP) The most dis\ntant objecfT of all the celestial scen\nery that is visible to the naked eye\nis the great nebula In Andromeda.\nWhoever first noticed it establish\ned a world's record for far seeing!\nthat can never be broken with the\neye alone. This remarkable nebula\nappears in the east in the evenings\nof October. It is easy to find.\nLook first for the square of Peg\nasus in the eastern sky; its cor\nners are marked by four bright\nstars. Suppose now Uiat the square\nrepresents the bowl of a very large\ndipper and look toward the left for\nthe handle.\nThe dipper figure of seven bright\nstars is not usually included among\nthe celestial dippers. The descrip\ntion is given formally only to the\nGreat Dipper and the Little Dipper\nin the north and to the Inverted\nMilk Dipper in the southern sky.\nBut it is a creditable dipper of its\nkind and directs the eye to the neb\nula. Look now at the second star in\nthe handle of this dipper figure.\nJust above the bright star and near\nly in line with it are two fainter\nstars. A little above the upper one\nand to the right there is a faintly\nluminous hazy patch. This is the\ngreat nebula in Andromeda.\nThe enormous distance of this\nobject became known only five\nyears ago when it was measured at\nthe Mount Wilson observatory. The\ndistance is 900,000 light years.\nTo find its equivalent in miles we\nmust multiply 186,284 miles, the!\nspeed of light per second, by 31,-\n500,000, approximately the number\nof seconds in a year, and then again\nby nearly a million. The result Is\nnot far from 6, 000, 000, 000, 000, 000,\n000 miles.\nTo the naked eye the Andromeda\nnebula is merely a dim glow. Phota\ngraphs with powerful telescopes\nshow It as a flat srjlral structure\npresented obliquely to us. It is the\nlargest and brightest of the spiral\nnebulae.\nThe spirals are huge aggregations\nof stars far more remote than the\nstars which for.m our constellations\nand even far beyond the Milky Way.\nSTREET IMPROVEMENT\nAWARDS GO TO COURT\nOsgood Avenue Property Owners\nRefuse to Accept Compensation\nBoard Finding.\nRuth N. Beach, Sofia Fodlasek and\nNarcyanna Bednarczyk have appeal\ned to the court of common pleas\nfrom the award of benefits and dam\nages by the board of compensation\nand assessment in connection with\nthe widening and improvement of\nOsgood avenue between Farmington\navenue and Corbin avenue. Hun\ngerford Saxe represent them.\nRuth N. Beach was awarded dam\nages of $1,200 and benefits of $440.\nthe latter being for a strip of land\nwhich the city will give her and the\nbenefit to her property reoresented\nby the improved highway, while\nSofia Podlasek was awarded $422.\n20. Nacyanna Bednarczyk was\nawarded nothing but assessed S1S7.-\n05.\nIn their appeal they ask a re\nappraisal of the damage to their\nproperties and a reassessment. The\nfindings of the board of compensa\ntion ana assessment have been ap\nproved by the common council, but\nthe appeal will cause a delay in the\nproposed improvement of the street.\nButler Boomed to Head\nDemocrats in Queens Co.\nNew York, Oct. 1 (P) Ellis Park\ner Butler, author-humorist todav\nmuch to his surprise discovered a\nfull-fledged boom under way to\nname him chairman of the Onwni\ncounty democratic committee.\nBut politics, Mr. Butler hastened\nto explain, was no new experience\nto mm. \"1 ran for president of the\nHand of Hope at Muscatine. Tnwn\nin 1884.\" he said, \"and 1 was elect\ned, too.\" \"But,\" he added, with n\nsigh, \"the society disbanded that\nyear. It just couldn't stand it, that\nwas all.\"\nThen somewhat anxinnsiv y,n\nasked: \"You don't happen to know,\ndc you. whether there's any salary\nattached? None? Heigh-ho. isn't\nthat always the way?\"\nFOR BEST RESULTS\nUSE HERALD CLASSIFIED ADS\nfefSftlES\nOFFICERS ELECTED\nBY SCHOOLSOCiETY\nUnited Parents and Teachers'\nAssociation in Annual Meeting\nHarry A. Witkin of 44 Tremont\nstreet, president of the Parent and\nTeachers' association of the Elihu\nBurritt school, was elected presi\ndent of the United Parents and\nTeachers' associations of New Brit\nain at the annual meeting held last\nnight in the board of education\nbuilding.\nMr. Witkin, who has done a great\ndeal to make the Elihu Burritt as\nsociation one of the most progres\nsive in the ity, is serving his sec\nond year as a selectman of the town,\nand is a past chancellor and pres\nent financial secretary of St. Elmo\nlodge, Knights of Pythias. He was\nin the U. S. Navy for two years dur\ning the World war, and is a mem\nber of the Eddy Glover post of the\nAmerican legiorf.\nOther officers elected last night\nwere: First vice president Russell\nC. Germond of the Lincoln school\ndistrict; second vice president, John\nE. Curtin of the Robert Vance\nschool district; secretary, Miss Ruth\nH. Jacobs, principal of the Israel\nPutnam school; treasurer, Miss Mary\nA. Tormay, principal of the Wash\nington school.\nStanley M. Hunt of the Lincoln\nschool district was appointed chair\nman of the organization committee.\nRoy W. Holtman of the Robert\nJ. Vance school district was appoint\ned chairman of the assembly com\nmittee. Ralph R. Mcrigold of the\nSmith school district was appointed\nchairman of the finance committee.\nDiscussion was held over the ad\nvisability of conducting a series of\nfour musical concerts during the\nwinter, bringing to New Britain some\nof the best known musical artists\nin the country, the proceeds from\nthe concerts to be put into the al\nmost depleted treasury of the\nUnited Teachers' association. A\ncommittee was appointed to study\nthe matter and reported to the as\nsociation. Louis P. Slade, principal\nof the high school, was appointed\nchairman, and Francis Clark and\nFrank Taylor were named other\nmembers of the committee. I\nAn alternate plan discussed was to\nhave a series of musical nights, us\ning all talent, and making a low ad\nmission charge. The talent would be\nrecruited from all schools In the\ncity if this plan is finall;- adopted\nby the committee.\nSING MASS FOR REPOSE\nOF ANDREA DEL SARTO\nCeremony Celebrated In Edifice\nWhich He Immortalized By\nServite Frescoes.\nFlorence, Italy, Oct. 1 (P)The\nmemory of Andrea Del Sarto. out\nstanding painter of the Italian\nrenaissance was honored yesterday\nby a solemn high mass chanted in\nthe church of the Annunziata. in\nwhose cloister are the frescoes of\nthe great artist. The ceremony was\nsupposed to coincide with the 400th\nanniversary of Del Sarto's death,\nthough some historians maintain he\ndid not die until 1531.\nOne of the painter's descendants\nis the French sculptor, Maxime Real\nDel Sarte, who though he lost his\nleft forearm in the war has produc\ned many notable statues, including\nthe widely-known one of Joan or\nArc which stands on the spot of her\nexecution, in the market place of\nRouen, capital of Normandy.\nAmong the novel features includ\ned in New York's (13-story Doherty\nbuilding will be double-decked ele\nvators which will take on and dis\ncharge passengers at two floors\nsimultaneously.\nI Wl W Mil I III I I I I W.I.IIM\nStop the embarrassing itching\nand get rid of the trouble with\nLResinoU\nCRUSADER\nby KUPPENHEIMER\nNews! Quality by Kuppenheimev\nis now within the buying reach\noi every man\nQuality clothes are so muck more prac\ntical, so muck more satisfactory, tkey\nshould cost more you should he willing\nto pay more. But now you needn't. The\nCrusader, despite its .modest price, hrings\nyou all the uuality tkat kas made Kup\npenheimer .famous Full weight wors\nteds preserve its styling. Dismiss the\nidea tkat good clotkes are expensive.\nGet tke most for your money, get quality,\nget satisfaction, wear a Crusader.\nQuality by Kuppenheimer\nN. E.\nKuppenheimer Clothes Knox Hats \"Manhattan Shirts\nNettleton Shoes Boys' Wear Sporting Goods\nLuggage Gifts Uniforms.\n$40\nSONS\n0","height":"25568","width":"19176"}}
